{{See Wiktionary}}{{Five kings of Wa}}
"Waō-kō" (also known as "Waō-kō") was a historical figure in Japan during the 5th century. According to the Chinese historical book "Sungshu," he was one of the five kings of Wa (an ancient name for Japan) and became the crown prince after the death of his father, King Sei. He was sent as a tributary to the Southern Dynasty of China in 462, during the reign of Emperor Taiwu of the Northern Wei, and was appointed as the General of the East and given the title of king of Wa. Some theories suggest that he is comparable to the Emperor Ankō in the "Nihon Shoki" (Chronicles of Japan).<ref>{{Cite web |last=日本人名大辞典+Plus |first=朝日日本歴史人物事典,デジタル版 |title=倭王興(わおうこう)とは？ 意味や使い方 |url=https://kotobank.jp/word/%E5%80%AD%E7%8E%8B%E8%88%88-1121321 |access-date=2023-01-21 |website=コトバンク |language=ja}}</ref>
Son of [[Sei of Wa|Je]] and brother of [[Bu of Wa|Wa]], one of the ''[[Five kings of Wa|Wa]]''. Some have compared him to the 20th [[Emperor Ankō]], others to [[Ichinobe no Oshiwa|Prince Ichibe Oshiwa]]<ref>"Hanzoku Wa-jin Kō" (漢籍和人考), first published by [[Kan Masatomo]] in 1892 (Meiji 25, [[1892]]). </ref>, [[Prince Kinashi no Karu|Kinashi no Karu]]<ref>"Ancient Japanese History" by [[Kunitake Kume]], first published in 1907 ([[1907]]). </ref> but has not been confirmed, as there is a theory comparing him to [[Kume Kunitake]].
{{Five kings of Wa Sources}}
